<Link id="l00029" /><CodeLine lineNumber="29"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// SparseBitVector is an implementation of a bitvector that is sparse by only</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00030" /><CodeLine lineNumber="30"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// storing the elements that have non-zero bits set.  In order to make this</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00031" /><CodeLine lineNumber="31"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// fast for the most common cases, SparseBitVector is implemented as a linked</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00032" /><CodeLine lineNumber="32"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// list of SparseBitVectorElements.  We maintain a pointer to the last</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00033" /><CodeLine lineNumber="33"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// SparseBitVectorElement accessed (in the form of a list iterator), in order</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00034" /><CodeLine lineNumber="34"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// to make multiple in-order test/set constant time after the first one is</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00035" /><CodeLine lineNumber="35"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// executed.  Note that using vectors to store SparseBitVectorElement&#39;s does</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00036" /><CodeLine lineNumber="36"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// not work out very well because it causes insertion in the middle to take</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00037" /><CodeLine lineNumber="37"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// enormous amounts of time with a large amount of bits.  Other structures that</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00038" /><CodeLine lineNumber="38"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// have better worst cases for insertion in the middle (various balanced trees,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00039" /><CodeLine lineNumber="39"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// etc) do not perform as well in practice as a linked list with this iterator</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00040" /><CodeLine lineNumber="40"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// kept up to date.  They are also significantly more memory intensive.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00041" /><CodeLine lineNumber="41"></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00274" /><CodeLine lineNumber="274"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// We cache a non-const iterator so we&#39;re forced to resort to const&#95;cast to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00275" /><CodeLine lineNumber="275"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// get the begin/end in the case where &#39;this&#39; is const. To avoid duplication</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00276" /><CodeLine lineNumber="276"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// of code with the only difference being whether the const cast is present</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00277" /><CodeLine lineNumber="277"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// &#39;this&#39; is always const in this particular function and we sort out the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00278" /><CodeLine lineNumber="278"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// difference in FindLowerBound and FindLowerBoundConst.</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00289" /><CodeLine lineNumber="289"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Make sure our current iterator is valid.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00290" /><CodeLine lineNumber="290"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordFlow">if</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> (CurrElementIter == End)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00291" /><CodeLine lineNumber="291"><span class="doxyHighlight">      --CurrElementIter;</span></CodeLine>
